Exploration of the Ford go-bike trips dataset¶

by Eric Makuochukwu Udeh¶

Introduction¶

The dataset at hand provides valuable information regarding the usage of a bike-sharing system in the greater San Francisco Bay area. This dataset contains data on individual rides made by users of the bike-sharing system, which can be analyzed to gain insights into patterns of usage and user behavior. With information such as the duration of each ride, the starting and ending points of each trip, and the type of bike used, this dataset is an important resource for anyone looking to understand the dynamics of bike-sharing systems and their impact on transportation in urban areas.

The analysis of this dataset seeks to explore the individual variables to get an idea of their distribution, as well as know the relationship between these variables with on another in order to answer some of, but not limited to the following questions below:

  • What age group use the Ford Bike sharing services the most?.
  • What percentage of riders are males, females or have undefined genders?.
  • What day of the week do we see more rides occur?.
  • What are the top 10 least visited start stations?.
  • Is there a relationship between the age of users and the general duration of rides?. How does the age distribution among user types compare?.
  • What proportion of each user types are made up of male, female and other genders?
  • What is the distribution by age of riders who use the bike sharing services on diffrent days of the week?
  • Are male rides really spending more time on rides as the cumulative time spent on rides by different genders suggest?

Quality issues observed from visual and programmatic assessment.¶

  • Columns that are irrelevalt to this analysis.
  • Missing values of start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name. As well as member_gender and member_birth_year.
  • Erroneous datatypes (start_station_id, end_station_id, and bike id should be strings. Member_gender and User_type should be categorical datatype. The age column should be in integer datatype.)
  • A member with birthyear of 1878. This looks out of order.

Data quality issue 3:¶

Define: Correct the datatypes of columns necessary.¶

Code¶

In [12]:
# Creating a function to convert given columns to categorical datatype
def to_categorical(column, category_list):
    category = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = False, categories = category_list)
    go_bike[column] = go_bike[column].astype(category)
In [13]:
# Calling the function above to change the member_gender and user_type columns to categorical datatype 
gender_categories = ['Male','Female','Other']
name_of_column = 'member_gender'
to_categorical(column = name_of_column, category_list = gender_categories)

user_categories = ['Customer', 'Subscriber']
column_name = 'user_type'
to_categorical(column = column_name, category_list = user_categories)
In [14]:
# Changing the datatypes of the columns start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id, as well as age column
go_bike[['start_station_id','end_station_id','bike_id']] = go_bike[['start_station_id','end_station_id','bike_id']].astype(str)
go_bike.age = go_bike.age.astype(int)

# changing the values of the start station id and end station id to whole numbers
columns_to_split = ['start_station_id','end_station_id']
for col in columns_to_split:
    go_bike[col] = go_bike[col].apply(lambda x: x.split('.')[0])

What is the distribution of ride duration like?

As we can see, it seems there are a lot more rides in the lower bound of the ride duration (rides less than say 10000 seconds. We can apply axis log transformation and changing of the bin sizes to get better insight.

In [26]:
# Changing bin sizes and applying log transformation on the x-axis
xbin = 10 ** np.arange(1.78, 5+0.1, 0.1)
xticks = [100, 300, 1000, 3000, 10000, 30000, 100000]
xlabels = ('{}'.format(v) for v in xticks)

plt.hist(data = go_bike, x = 'duration_sec', bins = xbin)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks(xticks, xlabels)
plt.xlim((60,86000))
plt.show()

Insight 4:¶

The chart is unimodal and shows that a good majority of the rides lasted less than 10,000 seconds. But there are a few others that lasted more than that, up to 86,000 seconds. Although, the number of these rides are so infinitesimal that they do not even appear on the chart.

Question 5:¶

What proportion of the User types are subscribers and customers respectively?

In [27]:
users_cat = go_bike.user_type.value_counts(ascending = False)

number_of_users = go_bike.user_type.shape[0]
max_count = users_cat[0]
max_prop = max_count / number_of_users
In [28]:
tick_props = np.arange(0, max_prop+0.1, 0.1)
tick_names = [f'{v*100:0.0f}%' for v in tick_props]

users_cat = go_bike.user_type.value_counts()
users_cat.plot(kind = 'bar')
plt.yticks(tick_props * number_of_users, tick_names)
plt.xticks(rotation = 0)
plt.ylabel('Proportions')


for i in range(2):
    count = users_cat[i]
    total_count = f'count: {count}'
    plt.text(i-0.15, count+2000, total_count)
plt.show()

Insight 5:¶

It can be noted that there are almost nine times as many subscribers as there are customers. i.e almost 90 percent of the riders are in the Subscribers category. Whereas, just a little over 10 percent are customers.

Question 6:¶

What day of the week do we see more rides occur?

Here we'll be plotting a seaborn countplot to see the relative distribution of the number of rides taken on different days of the week.

In [29]:
# Preparing the ticks for the relative frequency axis
day_of_week = go_bike.dow.value_counts(ascending = False)
number_of_days = go_bike.dow.shape[0]
max_number = day_of_week[0]
max_proportion = max_number / number_of_days
In [30]:
# Plotting the main chart
ytick = np.arange(0, max_proportion +0.02, 0.02)
ytick_names = [f'{v:0.2f}' for v in ytick]
color_scheme = sns.color_palette()[0]

sns.countplot(data = go_bike, x = 'dow', color = color_scheme)
plt.yticks(ytick * number_of_days, ytick_names)
plt.ylabel('Relative frequency of days')
plt.show()

Insight 6:¶

Thursdays see the most number of rides than any other days, while saturdays and sundays see the least

Distributions of our variables of interest.¶

  • The ages of riders had a unimodal distribution, with the histogram skewed t0 the right. Ages generally fell between 18 and 60 years of age, leaving some outliers above the age of 80. Axis limits had to be introduced to focus on the most important part of the chart.

  • The distribution of various genders shows that there are more than three times as many male riders as there are female riders. While other unspecified genders make up only a meagre 2.1%.

  • Finally, to get a clear picture of the distribution of duration in seconds, a log transformation of the scale had to be done.

Question 10:¶

In [35]:
# Creating a function for plotting violinplots. This will be used in the next two sections.

def violin_plot(x_axis, y_axis):
    violin_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.violinplot(data = go_bike, x = x_axis, y = y_axis, color = violin_color, inner = None)
    plt.show()

Question 12:¶

Which of the genders have spent more time (cumulatively) on rides?

Here we'll have to compare the total time spent on rides by each gender and compare using a bar chart of absolute frequency.

In [38]:
total_time_by_gender = go_bike[['member_gender','duration_sec']].groupby('member_gender', as_index = False).sum()
total_time_by_gender = total_time_by_gender.sort_values(by = 'duration_sec', ascending = False)
color_palette = [sns.color_palette()[0], sns.color_palette()[3], sns.color_palette()[6]]

plt.bar(data = total_time_by_gender, x = 'member_gender', height = 'duration_sec')
plt.ticklabel_format(style = 'plain', axis = 'y')
plt.xticks(rotation = 0)
plt.title('Chart of Total time spent on rides by each gender',fontsize = 16)
plt.xlabel('Member gender', fontsize = 13)
plt.ylabel('Total_duration spent on rides (s)', fontsize = 13)

for i in range(3):
    total = total_time_by_gender['duration_sec'].sum()
    duration = total_time_by_gender.duration_sec[i]
    props = duration/total
    percent = ('{:0.2f}%'.format(props * 100))
    plt.text(i-0.1, duration, percent)

Insight 12:¶

Male riders accounted for just over 71% of time spent on rides, while female riders and other gender accounted for about 26% and 3% respectively

Relationship between variables of interest.¶

  • There is no correlation (positive or negative) between the ages of riders and the time they spend on each ride. Although we can see that there are far more persons below the age of 50 who had rides surpassing 30,000 seconds.
  • It was observed that there are far more registered subscribers (8 times more) than there are customers using the bike_sharing service. Furthermore, there are three times more male subscribers than there are female subscribers.
  • The faceted histogram plot of age distribution by day of the week shows the age distribution of riders who use the go_ride bike-sharing service on each day of the week. While thursdays generally has the highest number of rides, saturdays and sundays have the least. One important take away from days of the week plot is that there are more riders who are between the ages of 25 and 35.
  • The violin plots of both age vs user_type and age vs member_gender show that a good majority of riders are above the age of 20, but below the age of 40.
  • Finally, male riders have cumulatively spend about 71% of the total ride time. This could as well be because there are more than three times more male riders than there are female riders. Further analysis would need to be done to ascertain this hypothesis.

Question 13.¶

Are male rides really spending more time on rides as the cumulative time spent on rides by different genders suggest? or is the higher total duration of rides as a result of higher number of male riders?

Here one would need need to generate a scatte plot of duration against age, while setting different markers for riders who are male, female or other genders. The presense of a certain marker appearing way up in the chart (higher duration of rides) would mean that the gender represented truly spend more time on a ride on average.

In [39]:
yticks = [100, 300, 1000, 3000, 10000, 30000, 100000]
ylabel = ['{}'.format(v) for v in yticks]

gender_marker = [['Male','s'],
                ['Female','^'],
                ['Other','o']]
for gender, marker in gender_marker:
    plot_data = go_bike[go_bike.member_gender == gender].sample(1740)
    sns.regplot(data = plot_data, x = 'age', y = 'duration_sec', x_jitter = 0.4, fit_reg = False, 
               marker = marker, scatter_kws = {'s': 7})
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.legend(['Male','Female','Other'])
    
plt.yscale('log')
plt.yticks(yticks, ylabel)
plt.show()

It is clear that the higher number of total time spent by the male gender over the female and other genders can only be attributed to the higher number of male riders, not necessarily that male riders, on the average, spend more time on rides.

One clear point to note though that there are more riders of the other gender who are above the age of 70 than there are either male or female riders.

Insight 14:¶

The clear pattern observed here is that:

  • most of the riders above the age of 50 are usually Subscribers. There is no clear pattern as to wether either subscribers or Customers take trips of longer duration than the other.
  • subscribers also dominate when it comes to rides below 300 seconds.

It is not clear wether any of the groups take longer rides than the other

Interactions between the variables of interest.¶

There was no clear indication that riders of a specific gender group or user type spend more time on rides than the others. So special attention would not need to be given to any of them. Although there are a lot more male riders than riders of female and other gender, more could be done to improve their inclusion, such as understanding why more women are not using the bike sharing service, and providing services that will attract more of them.

Interesting interactions between features?¶

While we can see that riders of all gender groups and user type basically spend same amount of time on the average, it is surprising that riders of the gender other as well as riders who are registered subscribers make up the population of riders above 70 years and 50 years of age respectively.

Conclusions.¶

In conclusion, some of the important take away from this analysis include:

  • There is neither a positive or negative relationship between ages of riders and time spent on each ride.
  • Thursdays get to see more rides than any other day of the week, while saturdays and sundays have the lowest number of rides.
  • The general ages of bike users fall between the ages of 20 and 40 years.
  • There are about three times more male riders than female riders. And riders of other genders make up just 3% of total number of riders.
  • While there are very few riders with gender other, this group make up the bulk of users above 70 years of age, as seen here
  • Gender doesn't play any role in the duration of rides by the customers or subscribers.
  • Most of the older riders are subscribers, rather than customers. And most rides that lasted up to 300 seconds were taken by this group of users.
